---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout>
    <nav
        class="w-full px-8 py-6 flex justify-between items-center border-b border-slate-200 dark:border-white/10"
    >
        <a
            href="/#work"
            class="text-xs tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 hover:text-slate-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors"
            >← Back to Home</a
        >
        <h1
            class="text-sm font-serif-elegant tracking-wide text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
        >
            Saurabh Sawant
        </h1>
    </nav>
    <main class="min-h-screen flex flex-col items-center w-full pb-32">
        <header class="w-full max-w-6xl px-8 pt-24 pb-16">
        <p
            class="text-xs tracking-widest text-teal-900 dark:text-amber-400 uppercase mb-4"
        >
            Unitree A1 · Oct 2024 - Apr 2025
        </p>
        <h1
            class="text-5xl md:text-7xl font-serif-elegant text-slate-900 dark:text-white leading-tight mb-8"
        >
            Multi-Robot Task Planning
        </h1>
        <div
            class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-xs tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-white/10 pt-8"
        >
            <span>ROS</span><span>•</span><span>Python</span><span>•</span><span
                >Behavior Trees</span
            ><span>•</span><span>gRPC</span><span>•</span><span
                >Cartographer</span
            >
        </div>
    </header>

    <div class="w-full max-w-6xl px-8 mb-16">
        <img
            src="/IDOGS_1.png"
            alt="Project Overview"
            class="w-full h-auto max-h-[70vh] object-contain rounded-2xl shadow-sm dark:shadow-none opacity-90 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-[#111]"
        />
    </div>

    <article
        class="w-full max-w-6xl px-8 text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-300 font-light leading-relaxed space-y-12 text-lg text-justify mt-8"
    >
        <section>
            <h3
                class="text-base font-bold tracking-widest text-teal-900 dark:text-amber-400 uppercase mb-6"
            >
                Overview & Mission Context
            </h3>
            <p>
                This project focuses on automating civil infrastructure
                inspections using a Multi-Robot System (MRS) to overcome the
                limitations of single-robot deployments, such as limited battery
                life, restricted range, and the risk of complete mission
                failure. The primary objective was to develop a modular and
                scalable Multi-Robot Task Planning (MRTP) framework using
                Behavior Trees (BTs) to coordinate multiple quadruped robots
                ("IDOGs") autonomously in a shared environment.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h3
                class="text-base font-bold tracking-widest text-teal-900 dark:text-amber-400 uppercase mb-6"
            >
                System Architecture & Methodology
            </h3>
            <p class="mb-4">
                To manage complex and concurrent inspection missions, the system
                architecture transitioned from traditional Finite State Machines
                (FSMs), which scale poorly, to a flexible Behavior Tree
                architecture.
            </p>
            <ul
                class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 marker:text-teal-900 dark:marker:text-amber-400"
            >
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Skill Subtrees:</strong
                    > Core robot capabilities, including autonomous navigation and
                    visual inspection, were designed as modular, reusable BT subtrees.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Task Assignment GUI:</strong
                    > A custom graphical user interface was developed using PyQt5
                    to allow operators to easily assign specific tasks to individual
                    robots dynamically.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Shared Localization:</strong
                    > Implemented a centralized communication system using a gRPC
                    protocol (Cartographer gRPC) to enable real-time localization
                    and shared mapping across the multi-robot fleet.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h3
                class="text-base font-bold tracking-widest text-teal-900 dark:text-amber-400 uppercase mb-6"
            >
                ROS Integration & Validation
            </h3>
            <p class="mb-4">
                The software stack heavily utilized ROS and the ros_bt_py
                library for execution, which was then validated on physical
                hardware.
            </p>
            <ul
                class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 marker:text-teal-900 dark:marker:text-amber-400"
            >
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Namespace Isolation:</strong
                    > Achieved scalable and isolated task execution by running independent
                    BTs within specific ROS namespaces for each robot.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Programmatic Execution:</strong
                    > Engineered custom Python functions that utilized ROS services
                    to programmatically load, add, and execute BT nodes and subtrees
                    based on instructions from the GUI.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Real-World Testing:</strong
                    > Successfully validated the framework using Unitree IDOG quadruped
                    robots in an indoor office environment, proving the system's ability
                    to navigate and perform visual inspections, such as detecting
                    electrical sockets.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h3
                class="text-base font-bold tracking-widest text-teal-900 dark:text-amber-400 uppercase mb-6"
            >
                Challenges & Implementation
            </h3>
            <p class="mb-4">
                Deploying the multi-robot system on physical hardware revealed
                several technical hurdles that required targeted engineering
                solutions.
            </p>
            <ul
                class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 marker:text-teal-900 dark:marker:text-amber-400"
            >
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Network Latency:</strong
                    > Running multi-robot localization via Cartographer gRPC introduced
                    latency and timing conflicts, which negatively impacted the effectiveness
                    of real-time collision avoidance between the robots.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >State Management Limits:</strong
                    > Because the ros_bt_py library lacked a native "blackboard" feature
                    for sharing variables between nodes, we had to engineer a workaround
                    utilizing the ROS parameter server.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong class="font-medium text-slate-900 dark:text-white"
                        >Topic Collisions:</strong
                    > Running multiple autonomous agents simultaneously required incredibly
                    strict namespace management to prevent ROS topic collisions.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
    </article>
    </main>
</Layout>
